Il Mulino New York (Miami) is an amazingly fine dining experience and an iconic restaurant in Sunny Isle Beach. The interior design and atmosphere of a restaurant can completely change the spectacle of eating out and carry the patron away from the sometimes monotonous continuity of day-to-day life. They value the ambiance almost as much as the actual food that is being served. Carlos Rodriguez, the Il Mulino’s General Manager is a very professional person with the proper attitude all the time. Very friendly, helpful and welcoming staff. Marvin is such a wonderful guy. Alina the hostess has a very pleasant attitude. We enjoyed this fabulous restaurant several times during our stay in Miami and every visit created unforgettable memories. The food is absolutely delicious, from the housewarming apps, to the main dishes, desserts, wine list....EXCELLENT! We’ll be back very soon!

Plenty of better options in the area.

This used to be my favorite restaurant (south beach location) but I stopped going once my favorite maÎtre d' Gianluca left. I met a friend at this location (Sunny Isles) today, for lunch and the staff themselves were very welcoming. My celebrity client, requested dinner for the evening to which we were told the restaurant was booked to capacity by the day mgr, but that he would see what he could do (dependent upon the weather) & for us to check back with the evening manager "Carlos" at 4:30. At that time, I went downstairs to personally speak with the manager, who would not come to the front and speak with me. I then tried calling 30minutes later from upstairs, to speak with him, and he would not even come to the phone. Throughout the evening we could literally see the outdoor seating from our upstairs balcony, which was clearly NOT AT CAPACITY.  Here's the thing, celebrity or not, any restaurant especially one that calls itself fine dining should have management that at least takes the time to try their best to work with any and all patrons. I have worked with hi level clientele for the past 20 years and have had to make the impossible, possible, across the country and have never had an experience where the manager will not even come out to speak with me let alone come to the phone, which is beyond insulting.  Again, I'd like to be clear that the wait staff were great during our lunch and this review is not to be a representation of their service. I just think it should be said, the carelessness of the evening manager should not be considered acceptable.

Last evening a friend took me to Il Mulino to celebrate my birthday.  The food was good but the service was very poor.  We were seated next to two mothers with their four young children, roughly between the ages of four and eight.  The children were very loud, so loud we could not converse.  The mothers, engaged in conversation and oblivious to their children, did not tell the children to keep the voices down.  An elegant, expensive restaurant like this is no place for screaming children.  My companion and I asked the waiter to move us to another table away from the children.  He proceeded to wait on other guests and ignored our request.  We approached the manager of the restaurant twice and asked him to move us to another table.  We were told there were no other tables available, which was not the case.  There were several empty tables available.  Finally, after a little more than a half hour, we were moved to another table.  My birthday celebration was ruined.  I would never return to Il Mulino after an experience like this.  Why didn't the manager speak to the mothers and ask them to get their kids under control?  Young children belong at Wendy's or McDonald's, family restaurants, not at upscale restaurants like Il Mulino.

HIT AND MISS FOR A VERY EXPENSIVE 5 STAR RESORT Expectations were high of course.  Service was impeccable.  I had requested 2 glasses of champagne when we are seated.  By the time they figured that out, our first course was served.  Amuse bouche was spicy fried zucchini chips.  Greasy, too spicy for the first thing.  Not good at all.   Chunk of Grana Padana was fantastic.  24 months aged.  Caesar was small portion but decent dressing.  A bit thin but good flavor.  Main problem was the Spaghetti Carbonara.  Flavor was good but pasta not al dente. Sent it back.  Came back a little more al dente but sauce was watery and bacon not cooked.  Amateur correction.  They used same batch of pre-cooked pasta and when added to the sauce, they took it out and plated so pasta would be more firm, but not long enough for sauce to thicken, bacon to get cooked and flavor intensify.  A shame.  Could have been a killer dish but lazy execution.  Mains were outstanding and honestly the only reason I gave Il Mulino 4 stars.  Salmon was fresh, delicious mushrooms with lemon zest and bright broccolini underneath.  Double veal chop was the star.  Cooked to perfection, bones were Frenched and crust was very tasty.  Not sure if it was worth $72 but it was clearly their signature dish.  Birthday dessert cake without warning and without offering any options.  That's bad management and someone should change that.  6 birthdays while we were there.  Same deal.  They asked if I wanted to see dessert menu after we ate the chocolate ganache.  Ugh.  I would return but for a 5 star, "best resort in the world" restaurant, my experience fell short of expectations as well as sloppy execution of dishes and requests.

He did not charge us for the lobster ravioli but he added  extra charges on our wine, our desserts...etc.  Therefore, at the end we paid pack the meal we have returned.  The super toscan was charged 28$ a glass instead of 16$, the dessert was charged 18$ instead of 11$, the coffee expresso was charged 10$...etc  The place is nice but you must check the invoice and if you are not satisfied, you can be sure they will make you pay somehow what you returned.
